snippet.textDisplay:
I mean honestly, minecraft's reality has a completely alien structure to it - it really is flat, but just like a tabletop doesn't fall down, the minecraft plane doesn't either. Gravity somehow originates from the Void, possibly because of it's very nature as a less-than-empty space - the negative energy (and therefore pull of normal energy) exerts something similar to gravity - energy pressure. Because of entropy, the world is always trying to enter this negative space and annihilate with it (just like you do when you fall into it - you fall out of the world, literally), becoming homogenously devoid. Perhaps gravity isn't even effected in a sphere, but a direct line upwards, which explains why the sky's light always falls directly downwards, and doesn't follow the sun in any way.

At the borders, the world begins to break down for unexplained reasons, until it is too damaged to be traversed - but people have been there, and there exists structure beyond the far lands, the far far lands, the index limits. It decays as you go further, most likely because the world out there has reached some sort of equilibrium with the void below and the cascading reaction has been stopped by the increased stability closer to the center of the world, which is inherently more orderly than the outer bounds.

A note to you, austin - if you want to rant and rave about real world physics applying to video games and then just accept interdimensional portals, you're being inconsistent; a stable wormhole would require negative mass to stay open, and a lot of energy to maintain, none of which we see during our construction of one. Perhaps the end portal draws energy from the end itself, but the nether one certainly doesn't.

I mean, most of the other "popular" wtf-moments in this game can be explained by inherent magic, or controlled chaos - steve obviously has telekinetic powers, what with the way he can punch 6 meters by gesturing, and can shrink and lighten objects substantially. If he has that power, and he's been born of the overworld, then why shouldn't the overworld's inherent power be the paradoxical stability over an infinite void? Steve simply draws upon it, most likely instinctually (consider zombies, who can wear gold armor, which would weigh like an actual ton irl), to make these things happen, especially when we see a clear instance of this macro-scale levitation of landmasses being a thing in the End, or in steve's gravity-defying creations which don't fall down, even though the game clearly supports such behavior. (another instance of steve applying this power by himself)

Also, the plane is made of a gride of geometrically perfect cubes with exactly zero seams anywhere (as seen by the existence of oceans), so the closest you could get to spherical worlds in this universe would be if spacetime was bent enough to create circles, which you couldn't percieve in any way, making the argument meaningless because it can't be proven.

And then there's the nonexistence of poles, and indeed, the completely random distribution of biomes. In order for "real-likfe biomes" to be the way they are, they require a specific position on the globe - sun hits head on, desert. sun hits at an extreme angle, icecap. The fact that we randomly encounter deserts, jungles and FROZEN OCEANS is not because the sun is somehow deeper in the horizon there, but most likely because of random, somehow permanent hot, cold, arid and humid zones. The nonexistence of dunes in deserts and the existence of grass beneath tundras also suggests that these zones wander, not giving the world time to accustom to them in the form of permafrost, for example.

The nonexistence of dunes in deserts and the existence of grass beneath tundras also suggests that these zones wander, not giving the world time to accustom to them in the form of permafrost, for example.

But it IS flat, in that it doesn't loop around. You cannot go around the Minecraft planet to return to the same point. It just keeps going, even on the old 32-bit versions where you find a wall at a certain distance where the terrain generation breaks down. Not only is it a flat plane, it is an infinite flat plane. Using science to prove it is impossible in the real world doesn't change that.

Actually, all that is necessary to show that it is possible is to assume that the vertical dimension has a certain thickness which gives enough mass to create sufficient gravity. That's it. The Minecraft universe is not our universe, and as such a plane of finite thickness and infinite extent is not impossible there. In fact, it is the only possible topology to explain the observed features of said world. Sine qua non, quid pro quo, et cetera, ad infinitum.

snippet.textDisplay: I'll probably gonna ruin this whole video and have to do it all again but this rotation thing actually could make sense in MineCraft. The error of this video is that the ground is tethered to the Sun. If that was the case, there would be no sunrise or sunset what-so-ever, the sun would always be at 90 degrees from the ground (as stated at 3:55). BUT! If the star was NOT the center of rotation and the world was rotating around something else, sunrises and sunsets would work fine and gravity would work fine too. The thing is that there is nothing always at 90 degrees that could be a source for the tether and rotation. In any way, this video fails when the sun is put as the center of rotation.
